            Slug = "chat-overview",
            Summary = "An overview of built-in chat: direct messages, channels grouped under teams, threads, links to people and records, sharing files, announcements, channel roles, and instant delivery.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 30,
            AppRoutes = """["/chat"]""",
            Tags = """["chat","communication"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Chat Overview\n\nForge has built-in messaging for talking with your coworkers, and messages arrive the moment they're sent. You can send private one-on-one messages, chat in shared channels, group channels under teams, reply in threads, link to records, attach files, and read company announcements. Open chat full screen from its own page, or slide it out from the chat icon in the top bar — that icon shows how many messages you haven't read. You can also **move chat into its own window** so it stays visible next to whatever you're working on.\n\n### Direct Messages\n\nA direct message is a private one-on-one chat with a single coworker. These sit in the **Direct Messages** section. Click **New Message**, search for a person by name, and start typing. Your message goes out right away — no need to refresh.\n\n### Channels\n\nA channel is a shared chat for a group of people. Channels sit in the **Channels** section and come in a few kinds: a **group** channel you create for a topic, a **department** channel, an **open** channel anyone can join, a read-only **broadcast** (announcement) channel, and channels the app sets up for you. Click **New Group** to make one — name, type, description, and people — or **Browse Channels** to find and join channels that already exist.\n\n### Teams\n\nA **team** gathers related channels under one heading you can open and close (for example, an Engineering team with its own set of channels). Team channels are set up for the team and listed together so people can find them fast.\n\n### Threads\n\nAny message can start a thread. Click **Reply in thread** on a message to open a side panel and reply without cluttering the main chat. A message with replies shows a **replies** link that reopens the thread.\n\n### Chat in Its Own Window\n\nWhen chat is the slide-out panel (not the full page), the top bar shows an **Open in window** button. Click it to move chat into its own window you can put on a second monitor and keep in view while you work elsewhere. While that window is open, the slide-out shows a **“Chat is open in a separate window”** note and the button becomes **Focus window** — click it to bring the window to the front. From then on, clicking a chat or channel in the slide-out opens it in that window instead of the panel. Close the window to go back to the normal slide-out. (There's only ever one chat window at a time; clicking again just brings it to the front.)\n\n### Links to Records\n\nMessages can carry links to records — a job, part, purchase order, sales order, quote, and more. A link shows up as a tappable colored label that opens that record's details. (These links, and tags of people, come on messages from elsewhere in the app. The message box is a plain text box for now — there's no name or record picker in it yet, so don't expect one to pop up while you type.)\n\n### File Attachments\n\nUse the paperclip button to attach a file up to 10 MB — a PDF, image, office document, or engineering drawing. The file uploads, shows a preview, and goes out with your next message. (You can attach files in channels.)\n\n### Announcements\n\n**Announcements** are posted by admins and managers and arrive the moment they're sent, showing up alongside chat and in read-only **broadcast** channels. An announcement can reach the whole company, one department, or specific teams; it carries an importance (Info, Warning, or Critical); it can ask people to confirm they read it; it can expire; and it can be built from a reusable template. You **write** an announcement from the **Admin** area, not from inside chat — chat is where announcements are *received and read*. Broadcast channels are read-only, so only admins and managers can post to them.\n\n### Channel Roles\n\nEach person in a channel has a role: **Member** (read and post), **Admin** (edit and manage the channel), or **Owner** (full control, including deleting it). You can see roles in the channel's settings.\n\n### Unread, Read, and Mute\n\nEach chat and channel row shows how many messages you haven't read, and the chat icon in the top bar shows your total. Opening a conversation marks its messages read. **Mute** a busy channel from its row to turn off its alerts without leaving it.\n\n### Instant Delivery\n\nEvery message, reply, and announcement arrives the moment it's sent — nothing to refresh. If your connection drops, chat reconnects on its own and catches you back up.","sections":[]}"""
